    <text id="B0359T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Walford sends Jackson a bill for school books, explaining the Tract Society's
                    policy about who should and should not have to pay for books.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Thos. P. Jackson, <abbr expan="Agent">Agt.</abbr></name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-09-04">1867 <abbr expan="September">Sep</abbr> 4</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>
                    <table>
                        <row>
                            <cell>272 Primers @ 5</cell>
                            <cell>13.60</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>60 <abbr expan="Primers">"</abbr> @ 20</cell>
                            <cell>12.00</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>72 Testaments @ 10</cell>
                            <cell>7.20</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>72 <unclear>Gems</unclear> @ 10</cell>
                            <cell>7.20</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>10 Gems @ 10</cell>
                            <cell>1.00</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell>$41.00</cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                </p>

                <p>Your letter to <abbr expan="Captain">Capt.</abbr>
                    <orig reg="McDonnell">McDowell</orig>, at Winchester, was referred through the
                    Bureau to this Agency of the American Tract Society with the request that we
                    would supply the books named therin on the terms proposed. We take pleasure in
                    so doing &amp; whenever we shall have received 1/2 the amount of above bill,
                    we will cancel the remainder by charging to our charity fund or rather to Grants
                    as we have <hi rend="underline">no funds</hi>. Provided: you will see that none
                    have books for nothing who are able to pay, &amp; none go <hi
                        rend="underline">without</hi> for want of money to buy. Please write us on
                    receipt of them &amp; whenever you can make it convenient let us hear from
                    the Schools.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Very Truly Yours</salute>
                    <signed>J. L. D. Walford<lb/><abbr expan="Agent">Agt.</abbr>
                        <abbr expan="American Tract Society">A.T.S.</abbr> per <del hand="h1"
                    /></signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
